		(effects
			(font
				(size 4 4)
				(thickness 1)
				(bold yes)
			)
			(justify bottom)
		)
		(uuid "80f44268-b6b5-4c84-91b1-22763672806c")
	)
	(text_box "Backlight Driver (Q3 - S8050 NPN transistor) - switches the LCD backlight LEDs under MCU control. R26 (1k) limits the base current from the MCU, R21 (10k) pulls the transistor off during MCU reset, and R27 (5Ω) limits the LED backlight current. The MCU drives DISP_BL, which turns the transistor on or off, allowing software brightness control or complete backlight shutdown. This works together with James' display load switch, which can remove power from the entire display subsystem for zero standby current."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 383.54 128.27 0)
		(size 76.2 21.59)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0.635)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 0 255 0 0.2)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(face "Arial")
				(size 1.27 1.27)
				(thickness 1)
				(bold yes)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "a9ed86c4-c745-4641-8a24-f5e79d521cce")
	)
	(text_box "Micro SIM Card (J8B - XUNPU MCS-302S-C1) - connects the RC7620 modem to the mobile network. U8 (TPD3S303DQDR) protects the SIM clock, reset and data lines from ESD events caused by handling or card insertion. C32 (100nF) provides local supply decoupling while C33 (33pF) filters supply noise on the SIM power rail. The modem communicates directly with the SIM through the standard ISO-7816 interface (VCC, CLK, RST and DATA). Unlike the SD card, the SIM power is generated and controlled internally by the RC7620 modem."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 256.54 63.5 0)
		(size 46.99 27.94)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0.635)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 0 255 0 0.2)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(face "Arial")
				(size 1.27 1.27)
				(thickness 1)
				(bold yes)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "b547516f-dfc0-4384-819f-d33a9be70f90")
	)
	(text_box "Load Switch (U7 - TPS22964CYZPR) - dedicated power switch added as part of the D-1 design improvement to prevent the MicroSD card from being powered during tray insertion. The switch receives the always-on +3.3V supply and generates a controlled output SD_VDD_SW, which powers only the SD card. C22 and C23 (1µF) provide input and output decoupling, while R29 (100k) ensures the switch remains off during MCU reset by pulling the ON pin low. The MCU drives SD_PWR_EN after detecting a stable tray insertion, allowing firmware to sequence SD power safely and eliminate the shared SIM/SD voltage bridging fault identified during testing."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at -43.18 218.44 0)
		(size 76.2 20.32)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0.635)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 0 0 255 0.4)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(face "Arial")
				(size 1.27 1.27)
				(thickness 1)
				(bold yes)
				(color 0 0 0 1)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "c6164863-0dfe-44f7-a83a-2a13cedbe4f9")
	)
	(text_box "Micro SIM card"
